                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "<system-reminder>\nAs you answer the user's questions, you can use the following context:\n# claudeMd\nCodebase and user instructions are shown below. Be sure to adhere to these instructions. IMPORTANT: These instructions OVERRIDE any default behavior and you MUST follow them exactly as written.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/CLAUDE.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# CLAUDE.md\n\nGlobal rules for all CloudZero repositories.\nRepo-specific overrides go in each repo's `.claude/rules/repository.md`.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/rules/collaboration.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# Collaboration Rules\n\nJoe has 30 years of architecture and development experience. Treat him as the\ndecision-maker on all non-trivial changes.\n\n- **Diagnose before acting.** When a bug or question is raised, explain the\n  suspected root cause and ask for input before writing any code.\n- **No unilateral code changes.** Do not edit files to \"fix\" something until\n  the approach has been discussed and agreed. Exploration (reading, grepping,\n  diffing) is always fine; writing is not until we've talked.\n- **One problem at a time.** Describe the issue clearly, propose one approach,\n  state what you don't know, and wait. Don't stack multiple changes in one\n  response.\n- **If you're wrong, say so.** Don't paper over a bad first fix with a second\n  fix. Stop, explain what went wrong, and start the conversation over.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/rules/jira-tickets.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# Jira Ticket Format\n\nHow to structure the body of a Jira task/sub-task/bug when filing new tickets. Applies to anything filed under CloudZero Jira projects. The goal is a ticket an engineer can pick up and act on without having to hunt for context.\n\n## Required sections\n\nEvery ticket has these four. Keep each concise — aim for scannable, not exhaustive.\n\n### Goal\nOne sentence: what outcome this delivers and for whom. Not a description of the work; the outcome of the work.\n\n### Scope\nBulleted behavioral changes. Include scope cuts (\"does NOT include X\") when they prevent confusion with adjacent tickets.\n\n### Technical details\nThe implementation-shaping context: existing code paths to reuse or replace, architectural constraints, interface contracts, schemas, perf/security/compat boundaries, known gotchas. Answers \"what should the implementer know before they start?\" Include specific file paths, class names, API endpoints where it helps.\n\nMay be brief for trivial tickets. Should never be skipped entirely on non-trivial work — if there's truly no technical context worth naming, the ticket is probably too small or miscategorized.\n\n### Acceptance\n`- [ ]` checkbox list of observable, verifiable criteria. Each should map to a command, UI state, API response, or test. Avoid internal assertions (\"function returns Y\") — describe what a verifier actually sees.\n\n### Related\nParent epic/story, blocked-by / blocks / supersedes links, key source files, and relevant docs. Link ticket keys and PR numbers explicitly (`CP-12345`, `#59`).\n\n## Optional sections\n\nAdd only when they carry weight for this specific ticket:\n\n- **Context** — when the \"why now\" isn't self-evident from Goal\n- **CLI contract** — when the ticket introduces a CLI verb or flag surface\n- **Config keys** — when adding managed-prefs, user defaults, or env vars\n- **Open questions** — architectural decisions to resolve during implementation\n- **Prereq / dependency** — operational blockers (certs, access, external team work)\n- **Explicit scope cuts** — standalone section when the boundaries with adjacent tickets are the main source of confusion\n\n## Conventions\n\n- **Checkboxes for acceptance criteria.** Always `- [ ]` so progress is visible in board views.\n- **Bug tickets** swap Goal for Symptom and add Expected vs Actual.\n- **No user-story \"As a… I want… So that…\" headers** unless the ticket is user-facing UX. They add noise to infra/build/refactor tickets.\n- **Actual newlines** in descriptions via the Atlassian MCP — never `\\n` escapes, never `\\[ \\]` escapes.\n- **Link shape:** `CP-12345` for tickets, `#59` for PRs, full file paths from repo root for source refs.\n- **Scope cuts belong in Scope**, not as an afterthought. If the reader of the ticket might do more than intended, say so explicitly.\n\n## Tooling — how to actually write the description\n\nJira Cloud stores bodies as ADF (Atlassian Document Format). Different tools handle markdown → ADF conversion differently, so the tool you pick is the difference between a crisp ticket and literal `##` / `- [ ]` eyesore text in the description.\n\n- **For anything with headers, bullets, inline code, or cross-ticket links** → use the Atlassian MCP's `editJiraIssue` with `contentFormat: \"markdown\"`. It does a proper markdown → ADF conversion: headings, bulletList, code marks, and links all render natively.\n- **For simple one-line descriptions or comments** → `jira-tool` (at `~/company/scripts/jira-tool`) is fine. But it does a naive paragraph-split on `\\n\\n` and treats everything else as literal text — so markdown syntax will NOT render.\n- **Create, then patch.** Use `jira-tool create` to file the ticket (it's quick and handles the parent/type/hierarchy rules cleanly), then immediately follow with `editJiraIssue` via MCP to rewrite the description properly. This is the workflow that actually works.\n- **Known markdown gap:** GFM task list `- [ ]` syntax is NOT converted to Jira's native `taskList` / `taskItem` nodes — it falls through as a regular bullet with literal `[ ]` prefix text. Still readable, but not clickable. Real Jira checkboxes require sending ADF directly (build the `taskList` node by hand). Optional — only worth the extra effort when clickability matters.\n- **Issue type string for jira-tool:** use `subtask` (lowercase, one word) when the parent is a Story. `task` fails with a hierarchy error.\n\n## Example skeleton\n\n```markdown\n## Goal\nMove CA cert generation from first-launch to pkg postinstall so MDM-pushed installs work without user action.\n\n## Scope\n- CLI: `CloudZero --register-certificate` (idempotent) + `--force` (teardown + regen)\n- Postinstall invokes as root; cert lands in System keychain (multi-user)\n- Existing first-launch retry stays as runtime fallback\n- Does NOT include managed-mode UI lockdown (see CP-NNNNN)\n\n## Technical details\n- Current gen logic: `app/CloudZero/Shared/Services/CertificateService.swift`, invoked from `AppDelegate.initializeInfrastructure`\n- System keychain: `/Library/Keychains/System.keychain`; trust via `SecTrustSettingsSetTrustSettings` with `kSecTrustSettingsResultTrustRoot`\n- \"Exists\" check must be expiry-aware (>= 30 days from expiry or replace)\n- Uninstall teardown already in `UninstallService.swift:40-49` — extend for System-keychain cert removal\n\n## Acceptance\n- [ ] `sudo installer -pkg CloudZero-X.Y.Z.pkg -target /` produces trusted cert in System keychain, no first-launch prompt under MDM\n- [ ] Back-to-back `.pkg` installs: same fingerprint (idempotent, no MDM-fleet churn)\n- [ ] `CloudZero --register-certificate --force` produces a new fingerprint, removes old trust entries\n- [ ] Near-expiry cert auto-replaces without `--force`\n- [ ] Uninstaller removes cert + trust cleanly\n\n## Related\n- Parent: CP-39713 (Apple Signing & Distribution)\n- Epic: CP-38896 (AI Telemetry Collector)\n- Related: CP-40345 (first-launch trust retry — stays as fallback), CP-40655 (restart-at-login race — this reduces surface area)\n```\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/rules/workflow.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# Workflow Rules\n\n## Feature plans live in `docs/features/`, not `tasks/`\n\n**Override** of the `.claude/rules/global.md` rule that says \"Write plan to `tasks/{JIRA-KEY}/PLAN.md`.\"\n\nFeature plans and design docs live at `docs/features/CP-XXXXX-short-name.md`, committed to the repo. Completed features move to `docs/features/done/CP-XXXXX-short-name.md`.\n\n**Rationale:** `docs/features/` is tracked, durable, and discoverable by humans browsing the repo. `tasks/` is gitignored, intended for ephemeral session scratch that shouldn't survive a branch switch or reboot. Plans are too valuable to throw away. The JIRA key in the filename makes plans discoverable via `ls docs/features | grep CP-40697` and mirrors the Jira URL directly.\n\n**How to apply:**\n\n- Filename: `CP-XXXXX-short-name.md`. The JIRA key is the identifier. `short-name` is a kebab-case slug of the feature. No sequential NNN prefix.\n- Multi-ticket features use the parent/epic key as the most representative identifier, and link the constituent tickets in the doc body. Pick the single best key rather than concatenating.\n- The plan's first-line title is the human-readable feature name (e.g., `# Install-time CA certificate registration`); the JIRA key appears on the line below. No need to repeat the number in the title.\n- Structure can follow the ai-sdlc `plan-jira.md` template (Current State / Problem Analysis / Implementation Plan / Verification) or a lighter shape if the task is simple. Match what existing `docs/features/*.md` files do — they're the living convention.\n- When the work ships, `git mv docs/features/CP-XXXXX-*.md docs/features/done/` as part of the final PR.\n- The ai-sdlc skills (`/new-session`, `/resume-session`) currently hardcode the `tasks/` path in their templates. Either tolerate the discrepancy (they'll write to `tasks/`, you can move content to `docs/features/` manually), or write the plan manually bypassing those skills.\n\n## Two-phase PR flow: plan review then implementation\n\nFor non-trivial work, review the plan **before** burning cycles on code. Reviewers (PMs, design partners, engineers outside the immediate work) can comment on the rendered plan in [mardoc.app](https://mardoc.app) — Google-Docs-style inline comments on markdown, no diff-reading required.\n\n**Phase 1 — Plan review PR (manual, not via `/create-pr`):**\n\n1. Commit only the plan file (`docs/features/CP-XXXXX-*.md`) to the feature branch.\n2. Push.\n3. Open a **draft PR** manually:\n   ```\n   gh pr create \\\n     --title \"CP-XXXXX: <summary> [PLAN]\" \\\n     --body \"Plan review before implementation. See docs/features/CP-XXXXX-*.md. Review in mardoc.app.\" \\\n     --draft\n   ```\n4. Reviewers comment in mardoc (or GitHub). Iterate on the plan. Amend/commit plan-only changes.\n\n**Phase 2 — Implementation (same branch, same PR):**\n\n1. Add implementation commits on top of the plan commit.\n2. When ready for code review, either flip draft → ready-for-review manually, or run `/create-pr` (which will detect the existing PR and run quality gates + Jira transition to Review).\n\n**Why not `/create-pr` for phase 1:** the ai-sdlc `/create-pr` skill is the \"we're done\" step — runs lint, runs tests, archives the task folder, transitions Jira to Review. None of that fits a plan-only draft.\n\n## Attribution\n\nNever include Claude attribution (`Co-Authored-By: Claude`, `noreply@anthropic.com`, \"Generated with Claude Code\") in commits, PRs, or issues. Enforced by a PreToolUse hook in `~/.claude/settings.json` that blocks any `git commit` / `gh pr` / `gh issue` command containing those strings.\n\n**Known conflict:** the ai-sdlc `/create-pr` skill's default PR body template contains `Generated with [Claude Code]`. The hook will block `gh pr create` calls carrying that string. Workaround: strip the attribution line from the PR body before the command runs.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/rules/global.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# CloudZero Global Rules\n\n## General\n\n### Core Principles\n\n- **Simplicity First**: Make every change as simple as possible. Impact minimal code.\n- **No Laziness**: Find root causes. No temporary fixes. Senior developer standards.\n- **Minimal Impact**: Changes should only touch what's necessary. Avoid introducing bugs.\n- **No Auto-Commit**: Do not automatically commit any files unless explicitly asked. Skills must NOT commit to git unless the skill's explicit purpose is committing (e.g., `/checkpoint`, `/create-pr`). All other skills leave changes uncommitted for user control.\n- **Do Not Edit Centralized Rules**: Files marked `DO NOT EDIT` are distributed via cz-build-common submodule. Changes must go through a PR to [Cloudzero/cz-build-common](https://github.com/Cloudzero/cz-build-common). Only `.claude/rules/repository.md` is yours to edit.\n\n## Task Management\n\n1. **Plan First**: Write plan to `tasks/{JIRA-KEY}/PLAN.md` with checkable items\n2. **Verify Plan**: Check in before starting implementation\n3. **Track Progress**: Mark items complete as you go\n4. **Explain Changes**: High-level summary at each step\n5. **Document Results**: Update `tasks/{JIRA-KEY}/PLAN.md` with review notes\n\n## Workflow Orchestration\n\n### 1. Plan Mode Default\n\n- Enter plan mode for ANY non-trivial task (3+ steps or architectural decisions)\n- If something goes sideways, STOP and re-plan immediately -- don't keep pushing\n- Use plan mode for verification steps, not just building\n- Write detailed specs upfront to reduce ambiguity\n\n### 2. Subagent Strategy\n\n- Use subagents liberally to keep main context window clean\n- Offload research, exploration, and parallel analysis to subagents\n- For complex problems, throw more compute at it via subagents\n- One task per subagent for focused execution\n\n### 3. Self-Improvement Loop\n\n- After ANY correction from the user: update `docs/project/LEARNINGS.md` with the pattern\n- Propose rules to the user to prevent the same mistake either in repository.md or the appropriate rule file in `cz-build-common`\n\n### 4. Verification Before Done\n\n- Never mark a task complete without proving it works\n- Diff behavior between main and your changes when relevant\n- Ask yourself: \"Would a staff engineer approve this?\"\n- Run tests, check logs, demonstrate correctness\n\n### 5. Demand Elegance (Balanced)\n\n- For non-trivial changes: pause and ask \"is there a more elegant way?\"\n- If a fix feels hacky: \"Knowing everything I know now, implement the elegant solution\"\n- Skip this for simple, obvious fixes -- don't over-engineer\n- Challenge your own work before presenting it\n\n### 6. Autonomous Bug Fixing\n\n- When given a bug report: just fix it. Don't ask for hand-holding\n- Point at logs, errors, failing tests -- then resolve them\n- Zero context switching required from the user\n- Go fix failing CI tests without being told how\n- If something is vague or unclear, ask for input.\n\n## System Interfaces\n\n### GitHub\n\nWhen interacting with GitHub use the GH CLI instead of the GitHub MCP server.\n\n### Jira\n\n- When creating Jira tickets, always follow `createJiraIssue` with `editJiraIssue` to set the description field.\n- When writing `description` fields via MCP tools, use actual newlines — do NOT use `\n` escape sequences (the Atlassian MCP tool double-escapes them into literal `\\n`). Same for brackets: use `[ ]` not `\\[ \\]`.\n\n#### Custom Fields\n\nThese fields are useful for when processing Jira tickets:\n\n| Field             | Key                 |\n| ----------------- | ------------------- |\n| Feature Team      | `customfield_10531` |\n| Feature           | `customfield_10680` |\n| Epic Link         | `customfield_10118` |\n| Start date        | `customfield_10525` |\n| Target end        | `customfield_10533` |\n| Actual end        | `customfield_10560` |\n| RFR               | `customfield_11505` |\n| Severity          | `customfield_10549` |\n| Est. Size         | `customfield_10623` |\n| InsightID         | `customfield_10595` |\n| Account           | `customfield_11093` |\n| Organization ID   | `customfield_11159` |\n| Support Requestor | `customfield_11472` |\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/rules/teams/cirrus.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# Cirrus Team Rules\n\n- **Feature Team**: Team Cirrus (`customfield_10531`: `10447`)\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/rules/failure-patterns/honest-engineering.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# Honest Engineering\n\nHow to plan and build without lying — to the user, the reader, or yourself. Referenced by the `value-cadence` skill; applies to any planning, estimation, or implementation work.\n\n## Principles\n\n- **No architecture theater.** Don't propose layers, abstractions, services, or interfaces beyond what the stated goal justifies. Every layer carries a permanent cost — read, debug, migrate. The bar for adding one is \"the goal cannot be met without it,\" not \"this is how mature systems look.\" When tempted to generalize early, name the concrete second use case; if you can't, don't build for it.\n\n- **Honest, ranged ETAs.** Estimate as a range (`1d`, `1–2d`, `3–5d`, `1w`), never a fabricated point. If the work is genuinely unknown, say \"uncertain\" and propose a timeboxed spike to buy the information — don't paper over the gap with a confident-sounding number.\n\n- **Evidence before build.** Zero-dependency probes that produce signal about quality, feasibility, or risk land in hours. Substrate-first / build-first plans defer that signal for weeks and routinely discover the hard problem too late. Sequence the cheap probe that could invalidate the plan first.\n\n- **Root cause, not papering over.** When a fix feels hacky or a second fix props up a first, stop. Diagnose the underlying cause and state it before writing more code. A workaround you can't explain the mechanism of is a guess, not a fix.\n\n- **No \"done\" without proof.** Don't claim work is complete, passing, or fixed until you've run the verification and seen the output. Report failures with their actual output; name skipped steps as skipped. \"Should work\" is not \"works.\"\n\n- **Surface what you don't know.** A plan with a stated unknown beats a plan that hides one. Flag the assumption, the missing input, or the risk explicitly rather than smoothing it into confident prose.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/rules/failure-patterns/communicate-efficiently.md (user's private global instructions for all projects):\n\n# Communicate Efficiently\n\nHow to write for a senior reader who is short on time. Referenced by the `value-cadence` skill; applies to plans, reviews, status, and any prose output.\n\n## Principles\n\n- **Lead with the answer.** The recommendation, conclusion, or result goes first. Reasoning follows for those who want it. Don't make the reader scroll to find what you decided.\n\n- **One-line entries.** Table cells, bullets, and list items are a single line each. No per-item headers, no nested preamble. If an entry needs a paragraph, it belongs in supporting material the summary points to.\n\n- **Senior-engineer register.** Assume the reader knows the domain. Cut throat-clearing (\"In order to...\", \"It's worth noting that...\"), restated context, and definitions of common terms. Say the thing.\n\n- **Don't restate the question.** Answer it. Echoing the prompt back as a preamble is padding.\n\n- **Pick one, defend it.** When a decision is called for, recommend a single option with its reasoning — not a survey of every option followed by \"all of the above\" or \"it depends.\" Surveys push the decision back onto the reader.\n\n- **No padding.** Cut hedging, filler transitions, and summary-of-the-summary closers. Length signals importance; pad and you misdirect attention. Under one screen unless the material genuinely demands more.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/CLAUDE.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# CLAUDE.md\n\nSee [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md) for project context, rules, and guidelines.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/jira-tickets.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# Jira Ticket Format\n\nHow to structure the body of a Jira task/sub-task/bug when filing new tickets. Applies to anything filed under CloudZero Jira projects. The goal is a ticket an engineer can pick up and act on without having to hunt for context.\n\n## Required sections\n\nEvery ticket has these four. Keep each concise — aim for scannable, not exhaustive.\n\n### Goal\nOne sentence: what outcome this delivers and for whom. Not a description of the work; the outcome of the work.\n\n### Scope\nBulleted behavioral changes. Include scope cuts (\"does NOT include X\") when they prevent confusion with adjacent tickets.\n\n### Technical details\nThe implementation-shaping context: existing code paths to reuse or replace, architectural constraints, interface contracts, schemas, perf/security/compat boundaries, known gotchas. Answers \"what should the implementer know before they start?\" Include specific file paths, class names, API endpoints where it helps.\n\nMay be brief for trivial tickets. Should never be skipped entirely on non-trivial work — if there's truly no technical context worth naming, the ticket is probably too small or miscategorized.\n\n### Acceptance\n`- [ ]` checkbox list of observable, verifiable criteria. Each should map to a command, UI state, API response, or test. Avoid internal assertions (\"function returns Y\") — describe what a verifier actually sees.\n\n### Related\nParent epic/story, blocked-by / blocks / supersedes links, key source files, and relevant docs. Link ticket keys and PR numbers explicitly (`CP-12345`, `#59`).\n\n## Optional sections\n\nAdd only when they carry weight for this specific ticket:\n\n- **Context** — when the \"why now\" isn't self-evident from Goal\n- **CLI contract** — when the ticket introduces a CLI verb or flag surface\n- **Config keys** — when adding managed-prefs, user defaults, or env vars\n- **Open questions** — architectural decisions to resolve during implementation\n- **Prereq / dependency** — operational blockers (certs, access, external team work)\n- **Explicit scope cuts** — standalone section when the boundaries with adjacent tickets are the main source of confusion\n\n## Conventions\n\n- **Checkboxes for acceptance criteria.** Always `- [ ]` so progress is visible in board views.\n- **Bug tickets** swap Goal for Symptom and add Expected vs Actual.\n- **No user-story \"As a… I want… So that…\" headers** unless the ticket is user-facing UX. They add noise to infra/build/refactor tickets.\n- **Actual newlines** in descriptions via the Atlassian MCP — never `\\n` escapes, never `\\[ \\]` escapes.\n- **Link shape:** `CP-12345` for tickets, `#59` for PRs, full file paths from repo root for source refs.\n- **Scope cuts belong in Scope**, not as an afterthought. If the reader of the ticket might do more than intended, say so explicitly.\n\n## Tooling — how to actually write the description\n\nJira Cloud stores bodies as ADF (Atlassian Document Format). Different tools handle markdown → ADF conversion differently, so the tool you pick is the difference between a crisp ticket and literal `##` / `- [ ]` eyesore text in the description.\n\n- **For anything with headers, bullets, inline code, or cross-ticket links** → use the Atlassian MCP's `editJiraIssue` with `contentFormat: \"markdown\"`. It does a proper markdown → ADF conversion: headings, bulletList, code marks, and links all render natively.\n- **For simple one-line descriptions or comments** → `jira-tool` (at `~/company/scripts/jira-tool`) is fine. But it does a naive paragraph-split on `\\n\\n` and treats everything else as literal text — so markdown syntax will NOT render.\n- **Create, then patch.** Use `jira-tool create` to file the ticket (it's quick and handles the parent/type/hierarchy rules cleanly), then immediately follow with `editJiraIssue` via MCP to rewrite the description properly. This is the workflow that actually works.\n- **Known markdown gap:** GFM task list `- [ ]` syntax is NOT converted to Jira's native `taskList` / `taskItem` nodes — it falls through as a regular bullet with literal `[ ]` prefix text. Still readable, but not clickable. Real Jira checkboxes require sending ADF directly (build the `taskList` node by hand). Optional — only worth the extra effort when clickability matters.\n- **Issue type string for jira-tool:** use `subtask` (lowercase, one word) when the parent is a Story. `task` fails with a hierarchy error.\n\n## Example skeleton\n\n```markdown\n## Goal\nMove CA cert generation from first-launch to pkg postinstall so MDM-pushed installs work without user action.\n\n## Scope\n- CLI: `CloudZero --register-certificate` (idempotent) + `--force` (teardown + regen)\n- Postinstall invokes as root; cert lands in System keychain (multi-user)\n- Existing first-launch retry stays as runtime fallback\n- Does NOT include managed-mode UI lockdown (see CP-NNNNN)\n\n## Technical details\n- Current gen logic: `app/CloudZero/Shared/Services/CertificateService.swift`, invoked from `AppDelegate.initializeInfrastructure`\n- System keychain: `/Library/Keychains/System.keychain`; trust via `SecTrustSettingsSetTrustSettings` with `kSecTrustSettingsResultTrustRoot`\n- \"Exists\" check must be expiry-aware (>= 30 days from expiry or replace)\n- Uninstall teardown already in `UninstallService.swift:40-49` — extend for System-keychain cert removal\n\n## Acceptance\n- [ ] `sudo installer -pkg CloudZero-X.Y.Z.pkg -target /` produces trusted cert in System keychain, no first-launch prompt under MDM\n- [ ] Back-to-back `.pkg` installs: same fingerprint (idempotent, no MDM-fleet churn)\n- [ ] `CloudZero --register-certificate --force` produces a new fingerprint, removes old trust entries\n- [ ] Near-expiry cert auto-replaces without `--force`\n- [ ] Uninstaller removes cert + trust cleanly\n\n## Related\n- Parent: CP-39713 (Apple Signing & Distribution)\n- Epic: CP-38896 (AI Telemetry Collector)\n- Related: CP-40345 (first-launch trust retry — stays as fallback), CP-40655 (restart-at-login race — this reduces surface area)\n```\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/scope/engineering.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# Engineering Rules\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n- Use the [Observability MCP](https://github.com/Cloudzero/ops-observability-mcp) to search logs, metrics, AWS x-ray and other items\n\n## Pull Requests\n\n- When the user says \"Create a PR\" or \"Make a PR\", run the `/create-pr` skill\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/scope/backend.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# Backend\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/repository.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# Repository Rules\n\nProject-specific rules and customizations for this repository.\n\n## Documentation naming and lifecycle\n\n### Feature plans — `docs/features/`\n\n- **Live plans:** `CP-XXXXX-short-name.md`. The Jira key is the identifier —\n  collision-free (issued centrally), URL-mirroring, and the token humans\n  grep and tab-complete for. No numeric or date prefix on live files.\n- **Shipped plans:** when the work ships, `git mv` the plan to\n  `done/YYYYMMDD_CP-XXXXX-short-name.md`, dated the day it shipped.\n  `ls docs/features/done/` is therefore the implementation timeline —\n  implementation order is stamped at the only moment it becomes a fact.\n  (A creation-date prefix would record when the file was written, which is\n  not the same thing and drifts from reality the moment priorities shift.)\n- **Historical files stay as-is.** Early `docs/features/` files used\n  sequential NNN prefixes (e.g., `028-ux-cli-field-update.md`,\n  `036-build-version-identity.md`) and pre-convention `done/` files are\n  undated. Don't rename them; backfill only if a need actually arises\n  (`git log --follow` already knows the dates).\n\n### Design docs — `docs/design/`\n\n- Numbered `NNN_short-name.md`, **append-only**: a new doc takes the next\n  free number; numbers are never reused, reordered, or reassigned.\n- **`docs/design/000_index.md` is the authority** for status (active /\n  superseded / review), supersession links, relationships, and the code\n  files whose comments cite each doc. A new design doc and its index row\n  land in the same PR — the index is also the merge-conflict lock that\n  surfaces two branches claiming the same number.\n- Status lives only in the index. The docs themselves are durable\n  present-truth: present tense, no changelogs, no status fields; when a\n  design changes, rewrite the affected sections in place.\n- `docs/design/ai-telemetry-event-schema/` keeps its own versioned scheme\n  (v0.0.N + CHANGELOG) outside this numbering.\n\n### Migrations — `db/migrations/`\n\n- Sequential `NNN_name.sql`, applied in lexical order. **Caveat:** two\n  parallel branches can both mint the same next number — coordinate before\n  taking one, and treat a duplicate-number merge as a conflict to resolve,\n  never to silently reorder. (Timestamp-named migrations would remove the\n  collision but require confirming the runner's ordering assumptions —\n  ticket that separately if the collision ever bites.)\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/global.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# CloudZero Global Rules\n\n## General\n\n### Core Principles\n\n- **Simplicity First**: Make every change as simple as possible. Impact minimal code.\n- **No Laziness**: Find root causes. No temporary fixes. Senior developer standards.\n- **Minimal Impact**: Changes should only touch what's necessary. Avoid introducing bugs.\n- **No Auto-Commit**: Do not automatically commit any files unless explicitly asked. Skills must NOT commit to git unless the skill's explicit purpose is committing (e.g., `/checkpoint`, `/create-pr`). All other skills leave changes uncommitted for user control.\n- **Do Not Edit Centralized Rules**: Files marked `DO NOT EDIT` are distributed via cz-build-common submodule. Changes must go through a PR to [Cloudzero/cz-build-common](https://github.com/Cloudzero/cz-build-common). Only `.claude/rules/repository.md` is yours to edit.\n\n## Task Management\n\n1. **Plan First**: Write plan to `tasks/{JIRA-KEY}/PLAN.md` with checkable items\n2. **Verify Plan**: Check in before starting implementation\n3. **Track Progress**: Mark items complete as you go\n4. **Explain Changes**: High-level summary at each step\n5. **Document Results**: Update `tasks/{JIRA-KEY}/PLAN.md` with review notes\n\n## Workflow Orchestration\n\n### 1. Plan Mode Default\n\n- Enter plan mode for ANY non-trivial task (3+ steps or architectural decisions)\n- If something goes sideways, STOP and re-plan immediately -- don't keep pushing\n- Use plan mode for verification steps, not just building\n- Write detailed specs upfront to reduce ambiguity\n\n### 2. Subagent Strategy\n\n- Use subagents liberally to keep main context window clean\n- Offload research, exploration, and parallel analysis to subagents\n- For complex problems, throw more compute at it via subagents\n- One task per subagent for focused execution\n\n### 3. Self-Improvement Loop\n\n- After ANY correction from the user: update `docs/project/LEARNINGS.md` with the pattern\n- Propose rules to the user to prevent the same mistake either in repository.md or the appropriate rule file in `cz-build-common`\n\n### 4. Verification Before Done\n\n- Never mark a task complete without proving it works\n- Diff behavior between main and your changes when relevant\n- Ask yourself: \"Would a staff engineer approve this?\"\n- Run tests, check logs, demonstrate correctness\n\n### 5. Demand Elegance (Balanced)\n\n- For non-trivial changes: pause and ask \"is there a more elegant way?\"\n- If a fix feels hacky: \"Knowing everything I know now, implement the elegant solution\"\n- Skip this for simple, obvious fixes -- don't over-engineer\n- Challenge your own work before presenting it\n\n### 6. Autonomous Bug Fixing\n\n- When given a bug report: just fix it. Don't ask for hand-holding\n- Point at logs, errors, failing tests -- then resolve them\n- Zero context switching required from the user\n- Go fix failing CI tests without being told how\n- If something is vague or unclear, ask for input.\n\n## System Interfaces\n\n### GitHub\n\nWhen interacting with GitHub use the GH CLI instead of the GitHub MCP server.\n\n### Jira\n\n- When creating Jira tickets, always follow `createJiraIssue` with `editJiraIssue` to set the description field.\n- When writing `description` fields via MCP tools, use actual newlines — do NOT use `\n` escape sequences (the Atlassian MCP tool double-escapes them into literal `\\n`). Same for brackets: use `[ ]` not `\\[ \\]`.\n\n#### Custom Fields\n\nThese fields are useful for when processing Jira tickets:\n\n| Field             | Key                 |\n| ----------------- | ------------------- |\n| Feature Team      | `customfield_10531` |\n| Feature           | `customfield_10680` |\n| Epic Link         | `customfield_10118` |\n| Start date        | `customfield_10525` |\n| Target end        | `customfield_10533` |\n| Actual end        | `customfield_10560` |\n| RFR               | `customfield_11505` |\n| Severity          | `customfield_10549` |\n| Est. Size         | `customfield_10623` |\n| InsightID         | `customfield_10595` |\n| Account           | `customfield_11093` |\n| Organization ID   | `customfield_11159` |\n| Support Requestor | `customfield_11472` |\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/teams/cirrus.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# Cirrus Team Rules\n\n- **Feature Team**: Team Cirrus (`customfield_10531`: `10447`)\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/tech/makefile.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# Makefile Rules\n\n## Standard Commands\n\n| Command                       | Description                                            |\n| ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |\n| `make init`                   | Install dependencies (creates venv, installs dev deps) |\n| `make lint`                   | Run linting (ruff check + format check)                |\n| `make lint-fix`               | Auto-fix lint and formatting issues                    |\n| `make test`                   | Run unit tests (80% coverage required)                 |\n| `make check`                  | Run lint + test together                               |\n| `make lock-requirements`      | Compile requirements with uv                           |\n| `make lock-requirements-dev`  | Dev dependencies only                                  |\n| `make lock-requirements-prod` | Prod dependencies only                                 |\n| `make build`                  | Build the application                                  |\n\n## Deployment Commands\n\n```bash\nmake namespace=alfa deploy         # Deploy to dev\nmake namespace=alfa get-api-info   # Get API info after deploy\nmake namespace=alfa run-setup      # Configure the feature\nmake namespace=alfa smoke          # Run smoke tests\nmake namespace=alfa describe       # Describe CloudFormation stack\nmake namespace=alfa delete         # Tear down the stack\nmake namespace=alfa deploy-dry-run # Validate and package before deployment\n```\n\nAlways chain AWS auth: `updc && make namespace=alfa deploy`\n\n## Frontend Commands\n\n| Command                              | Description          |\n| ------------------------------------ | -------------------- |\n| `yarn build:all` or `make build-all` | Build all packages   |\n| `yarn install` or `make init`        | Install dependencies |\n| `yarn test:lint`                     | Run linter           |\n| `yarn test:typecheck`                | Type checking        |\n| `yarn test:unit`                     | Run unit tests       |\n\n## Conventions\n\n- Always run `make lint-fix` and `make check` after making code changes\n- Use `make help` to show all available commands in any project\n- MakefileConstants.mk provides per-repo overrides (FEATURE_NAME, SRC_DIRS, etc.)\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/company/code/cloudzero/feature-ai-collector-macos/.claude/rules/tech/aws.md (project instructions, checked into the codebase):\n\n# AWS Rules\n\n## General\n\n- When accessing AWS, strongly prefer to use the `AWSReadOnlyAccess` role for read only actions.\n\nContents of /Users/joe.barnett/.claude/projects/-Users-joe-barnett-company-code-cloudzero-feature-ai-collector-macos/memory/MEMORY.md (user's auto-memory, persists across conversations):\n\n# Memory Index\n- [Cowork cost on the wire](cowork-cost-on-wire.md) — Cowork token/cost lives in `event_logging/v2/batch` TelemetryEvents, not completion streams; corrects CP-41575.\n# userEmail\nThe user's email address is joe.barnett@cloudzero.com.\n# currentDate\nToday's date is 2026-06-15.\n\n      IMPORTANT: this context may or may not be relevant to your tasks. You should not respond to this context unless it is highly relevant to your task.\n</system-reminder>\n\n"
